<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec_duality2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Working with Duality</title>

    <subsubsection>
        <title>Activities</title>
        
        <activity>
            <title>Double-slit Electrons</title>
            <introduction>
            <p>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                Suppose electrons with speed <m>v = 10^4 \mathrm{~m/s}</m> are sent through a double-slit experiment with <m>d = 1.5 \mathrm{~mm}</m>.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the wavelength of each electron in nanometers.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the angle to the first constructive point?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    How would each of your previous answers change if the speed of each electron were <m>v = 10^6 \mathrm{~m/s}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        </activity>

        <activity>
            <title>Momentum of a Photon</title>
            <introduction>
            <p>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                A particle with mass has a wavelength <me>\lambda = \frac{h}{p}</me>  
                Suppose that the this equation were also valid for a photon, which is massless and has energy given by <me>E = \frac{hc}{\lambda}</me>  
            </p>
        </introduction>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Use these equations to write a relationship between the energy and momentum of a photon.  Check the fundamental units of this equation to confirm its accuracy.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        The special theory of relativity expresses the following relationship between energy and momentum for all particles: <me>E^2 = (pc)^2 + (mc^2)^2</me>  
                        Show that this equation agrees with the relationship you found above for a massless photon.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Investigate the energy-momentum relation above for a particle with mass <m>m</m> that is <em>at rest</em> (that is, with no momentum).  Is the result a familiar one?
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
        </activity>

        <activity>
            <title>Wavelength and Energy</title>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    
                </p>
                <p>
                    You conduct an experiment using two slits separated by <m>2500 \mathrm{~nm}</m> and observe a two-slit interference pattern.  You measure the angle to the first maximum to be <m>0.164 \mathrm{~rad}</m>.
                </p>
            </introduction>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        If the experiment was conducted with photons, determine the wavelength, frequency, and energy of each individual photon.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                       If the experiment was conducted with electrons, determine the wavelength, velocity, and energy of each individual electron. 
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Compare the wavelengths and the energies of the two particles.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
        </activity>
        
    </subsubsection>
    


</section>